[[File:Bafa edu logo 400x389.png|thumb]] {{use mdy dates|date=November 2016}} {{non-free|date=July 2015}} }}
'''BaFá BaFá''' is a face-to-face learning [[simulation]] (game), invented by Dr. R. Garry Shirts in 1974,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dukes|first1=Richard L.|last2=Fowler|first2=Sandra M.|last3=Dekoven|first3=Bernie|title=R. Garry Shirts Simulation Gaming Exemplar|journal=Simulation & Gaming|date=October 2011|volume= 42|issue= 5 |pages=545–570|url=http://sag.sagepub.com/content/42/5/545.short |doi=10.1177/1046878111424335 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dekoven|first1=Bernie|title=Garry Shirts - A Life Created|url=https://www.academia.edu/1897057/R._Garry_Shirts|website=Academia.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Blanca|title=Educational psychologist was pioneer in simulation training|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2011/may/16/educational-psychologist-was-pioneer-in/|accessdate=April 30, 2015|newspaper=The San Diego Union-Tribune |date=May 16, 2011}}</ref> who also invented [[StarPower (game)|StarPower ]], and is published by Simulation Training Systems, Inc. The simulation is intended to improve participants' cross-[[cultural competence]] by helping them understand the impact of culture on the behavior of people and organizations. Participants experience "culture shock" by traveling to and trying to interact with a culture in which the people have different values, different ways of behaving and different ways of solving problems. There are three versions, one for high schools, charities and universities,<ref>{{cite web|title=BaFa' BaFa' - Culture/Diversity for Schools & Charities|url=http://www.simulationtrainingsystems.com/schools-and-charities/products/bafa-bafa/|website=Simulation Training Systems|accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref> one for middle school aged children called '''RaFá RaFá''',<ref>{{cite web|title=Rafa' Rafa' - Cultural Diversity Game|url=http://www.simulationtrainingsystems.com/schools-and-charities/products/rafa-rafa/|website=Simulation Training Systems|accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref> and a professional version<ref>{{cite web|title=Professional BaFa' BaFa' - A Cross Culture/Diversity Simulation|url=http://www.simulationtrainingsystems.com/corporate/products/bafa-bafa/|website=Simulation Training Systems}}</ref> for business and government agencies.
==Origin== "Around 1971, the U.S. Navy became very concerned about the behavior of American Sailors on leave in foreign ports, specifically Greece and Japan, and determined to do something to avoid incidents that were threatening relations between the United States and its allies. The Navy Personnel Research and Development Center approached Garry Shirts for assistance in creating a simulation that would teach naval personnel about the specific cultures where incidents had occurred.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yellen|first1=Ted M I|last2=Hoover|first2=Margaret W|title=In-Country Experience: Navy Personnel Stationed in Greece.|url=http://oai.dtic.mil/oai/oai?verb=getRecord&metadataPrefix=html&identifier=ADA123184|website=DTIC.mil|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref> The Navy had created print material, readily available to the sailors, that explained Greek culture, so a lack of information was not the problem; it was the apparent failure to put it to use.
Shirts decided that educating people was only part of the answer; it was also necessary to help them understand the nature of culture itself and its impact on human interaction. This would, he postulated, motivate them to learn how to interact effectively within any cultural environment. The result was the simulation game BaFá BaFá, which was originally accompanied by training modules, a comic strip, and language tapes. This was the first intercultural simulation, and when it was made generally available in 1974, it became the most widely used and well-known simulation in the field (Shirts 1974, 1975). It was founded on the idea of having trainees learn and become members of two contrasting cultures, Alpha and Beta, and then visiting each other. One is a more collectivist, people-oriented, touching culture, and the other, using a different language, is more individualistic and task oriented. The point of the interaction between members of the two cultures is to teach "that what seems irrational, contradictory, or unimportant to us in our culture may seem rational, consistent, and terribly important in another culture" (Shirts, 1995). Other simulations have been created in the field, but all owe some credit for inspiration to this one, the classic that has provided a model for intercultural simulation games."<ref>{{cite book|editor=Bennett Dan Landis |editor2=Janet M. Bennett |editor3=Milton J.|title=Handbook of intercultural training |year=2004 |publisher=Sage Publications |location=Thousand Oaks, Calif. |isbn=9780761923329 |page=20 |edition=3rd |url=http://www.sagepub.com/refbooks/Book226202 |accessdate=April 30, 2015}} {{subscription}}</ref>
==Uses== BaFá BaFá is adaptable<ref>{{cite book|editor=Bennett Dan Landis |editor2=Janet M. Bennett |editor3=Milton J.|title=Handbook of intercultural training |date=2004 |publisher=Sage Publications |location=Thousand Oaks, Calif. |isbn=9780761923329 |pages=62–63 |edition=3rd |url=http://www.sagepub.com/refbooks/Book226202 |accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref> and has been used in many different settings including with any groups that have different cultures, whether because of geographical location, political beliefs, race, organizational structure, mergers, sexual orientation, etc. Some examples of ways it has been used: * Training or teaching about diversity/inclusion.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shirts |first1=R. Garry |title=BaFa' BaFa' Train The Trainer: When Used For Diversity |url=https://www.indstate.edu/diversity/docs/Bafa-Diversity-10-01-09.pdf |website=Indiana State University |publisher=Indiana State University office of Diversity |accessdate=April 30, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412004907/http://www.indstate.edu/diversity/docs/Bafa-Diversity-10-01-09.pdf |archivedate=April 12, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Using Exercises and Simulations to Engage Students|url=http://www.uww.edu/learn/improving/aboutdiversity/approachdiversity/exercisessimulations|website=Learn Center-Diversity and Inclusion-An Approach for Teaching Diversity-Triggers|publisher=University of Wisconsin, Whitewater|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref> * Sociology classes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Persell|first1=Caroline H|last2=Gerdes|first2=Jennifer|title=Lesson Plan for NYU Intro to Sociology|url=http://www.nyu.edu/classes/persell/aIntroNSF/LessonPlans/BAFABAFALesson%20Plan.htm|website=New York University|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref> * Management Training.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bickley|first1=Maureen|title=Using an Experiential Simulation to Build Cross Cultural Understanding: a Qualitative Study of Graduate Students|url=http://espace.library.curtin.edu.au/R?func=dbin-jump-full&local_base=gen01-era02&object_id=21020|website=Curtin University|publisher=Curtin University of Technology, Graduate School of Business|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref> * Preparing people to travel to different cultures (Peace Corps,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sauer|first1=Janet|last2=Sauer|first2=Chris|title=Challenging Pre-service Teachers’ Understanding of the Intersection of Disability and Cultural Diversity|journal=Journal of Praxis in Multicultural Education|date=2010|volume=5|issue=1|pages=23–35|url=http://www.uccs.edu/Documents/coe/people/faculty/sauerj/ChallengingTeachersUnderstanding.pdf|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref> missionaries, military<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yellen|first1=Ted M. I.|title=The Cross-cultural Interaction Inventory: Development of Overseas Criterion Measures and Items That Differentiate Between Successful and Unsuccessful Adjusters |url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a009362.pdf|website=DTIC.mil|publisher=Navy Personnel Research and Development Center|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Abbe, Ph.D|first1=Allison|last2=Gouge|first2=Melissa|title=Cultural Training for Military Personne l- Revisiting the Vietnam Era|url=http://usacac.army.mil/CAC2/MilitaryReview/Archives/English/MilitaryReview_20120831_art005.pdf|website=United States Army Combined Arms Center|accessdate=April 30, 2015}}</ref>). * Medical professionals,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Blackburn |first1=Donna S.|title=Nursing Students' Perceptions of a Simulation Game to Promote Cultural Sensitivity|url=http://www.nursinglibrary.org/vhl/handle/10755/150970|website=Virginia Henderson International Nursing e-Repository|accessdate=May 1, 2015|date=2009}}</ref> staff and educators. * Orientations (student<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cook|first1=John|last2=Martinez|first2=Sergio|title=Diversity Dimension Report|url=https://www.utb.edu/vpaa/foe/Documents/Foundational%20Dimensions/Diversity.pdf|website=University of Texas at Brownsville|accessdate=May 1, 2015}}</ref> and staff).
